    • Method Detail

      • blockAndWaitFor

        <T> T blockAndWaitFor(Supplier<? extends T> blockingSupplier,
                      QualifiedName namespace,
                      DataSource id)
        Blocks are intended to signal that a thread is waiting for resources to be made available by some external process.

        This method will block completion of the BindingFuture until the given runnable process completes. The process will be completed on the invoking thread, so invocation returns only after the supplier completes execution and the block is lifted.

        Blocks may be satisfied by external processes, so if a block is still in place when binding otherwise completes, with no internal processing threads remaining unblocked, then the binding will simply wait until the supplier delivers the dependency.

        The thread which the given blocking process is invoked on will always terminate after invocation, and after releasing the block. This can be useful for synchronisation, as the thread which provided the dependency can Thread.join() onto this thread before blocking itself on a difference resource, potentially causing an erroneous deadlock detection.

        Parameters:
        blockingSupplier - The runnable which will block until its execution completes
        namespace - The namespace of the blocking resource
        id - The id of the blocking resource
        Returns:
        The new thread which is performing the blocking resource fetching

        default Thread blockFor(Runnable blockingRunnable,
                        QualifiedName namespace,
                        DataSource id)
        Blocks are intended to signal that a thread is waiting for resources to be made available by some external process.

        This method will block completion of the BindingFuture until the given runnable process completes. The process will be completed on another thread, so invocation returns immediately.

        The thread which the given blocking process is invoked on will always terminate after invocation, and after releasing the block.       • blockAndWaitForInteral

        <T> T blockAndWaitForInteral(Supplier<? extends T> blockingSupplier,
                             QualifiedName namespace,
                             DataSource id)
        Internal blocks are intended to signal that a thread is waiting for resources to be made available by other threads participating in the binding/unbinding process.

        This method will block completion of the BindingFuture until the given runnable process completes. The process will be completed on the invoking thread, so invocation returns only after the supplier completes execution and the block is lifted.

        Internal blocks must be satisfied by internal processes, so if an internal block is still in place when binding otherwise completes, with no external blocks in place and no internal processing threads remaining unblocked, then the binding will fail due to unsatisfied dependency.

        The thread which the given blocking process is invoked on will always terminate after invocation, and after releasing the block. This can be useful for synchronisation, as the thread which provided the dependency can Thread.join() onto this thread before blocking itself on a difference resource, potentially causing an erroneous deadlock detection.

        Parameters:
        blockingSupplier - The runnable which will block until its execution completes
        namespace - The namespace of the blocking resource
        id - The id of the blocking resource
        Returns:
        The new thread which is performing the blocking resource fetching
